AGI - Spanish premier Pedro Sanchez> announced that he will not resign and will continue to lead the executive "with even more force, if possible", after the period of reflection taken<a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-04-24/indagata-moglie-sanchez-dimissioni-26158186/"> in the days he has been accused Campaign that, Sanchez said, "will not stop, I can handle it."
&nbsp;
The decision, of which no one had been informed in the premier's entourage, was taken at the end of five days of reflection following the open investigation towards the consort of Sanchez for traffic of influences and corruption.&nbsp; In these days the tenant of the Moncloa received a wave of solidarity from socialist militants and leaders who asked him not to take a step back. Sanchez admitted that "social mobilization weighed" on his decision to stay at Moncloa, a decision that is "a firm point, I guarantee it", he said in front of the cameras. "There is only one way to reverse this situation, that the social majority, as it has done in these five days, mobilize in a firm commitment to dignity and good sense, putting an end to the policy of shame that we have been undergoing for too long," he said.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
In recent days Sanchez had denounced a campaign of "vesting and demolition" against Gomez by the opposition, in particular the People's Party and Vox, and other media and organizations of right and extreme right. The premier was then locked up with his wife and daughters for five long days in the seat of the government>&nbsp; where he has an apartment, without sharing with anyone else the decision-making process. From the "well informed" environments it was wrong that Sanchez had thought to leave after learning about the complaint against his wife, but that, not to act quickly, he had decided to give himself a few days of reflection, as he explained in his letter to the citizens.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The Psoe had therefore transformed the meeting of its Federal Committee on Saturday, intended to approve the candidatures in the European elections, in an act of support to its leader in which the appeals were repeated not to throw the sponge. "Pedro, resta", was the message with which the 'number two' of the government and the Psoe, Maria Jesus Montero, had opened his intervention in the socialist conclave, supported by the rest of the party leaders and, in the square, by several thousand militants who came to Madrid from all over Spain to support their general secretary. There were also other mobilizations during the weekend that asked Sanchez to remain in the leadership of the government. For his part, the president of the PP, Alberto Nunez Feijoo, declared that Sanchez, whatever he had decided, already represented the past having brought "decadency and division" to Spain.

